AGI -&nbsp;Claudia Sheinbaum> enters history as the first female president of Mexico>, passing by consensus the electoral victory of his predecessor and party companion, Andres Manuel Lopez Obrador>, in 2018. The sixty-year-old Sheinbaum, an environmental scientist for training, has led the capital city of Mexico over the last five years and will take the presidency in almost four months, from October 1st. He obtained almost 60% of the votes according to the first data, exceeding about 30 points his main opponent of the opposition party Xòchitl Gàlvez>, who admitted the defeat, while in third place Jorge lvarez Màynez> was voted by about 10%.
&nbsp;
The breadth of victory, in the country with little less than 100 million voters, has also exceeded the wide one already foreseen by the polls. As the next president said, thanking the "millions of Mexican women and men who decided to vote for us on this historic day for the recognition of our transformation project". Lòpez Obrador, on his part, pointed out that "the Mexican people freely and democratically decided that Claudia Sheinbaum would become the first female president of Mexico after 200 years, from 1824, from the first federal republic, since Guadalupe Victoria was the first president, but also the elected one with the greatest number of votes throughout the history of our country."
&nbsp;
The coalition that supports it, composed of the National Regeneration Movement (Morena), the Labour Party (PT) and the Green Ecology of Mexico (PVEM), obtained the &nbsp; majority of the two-thirds of the Chamber of Deputies><span>. This will allow the president to promote the controversial constitutional reforms proposed by his predecessor as the militarization of the National Guard, the reform of the electoral system and the election by popular vote of the judges and members of the Supreme Court.</span>
<div </div
The party to the government also confirmed the management of its main political stronghold, Mexico City, where Clara Brugada earned almost 10 points of advantage on the opponent Santiago Taboada, despite the polls predicted a less marked victory.
<h2> The shadow of the Narcos on the vote &nbsp;</h2>
In a country where politics, crime and corruption are closely interwoven, drug cartels > have done everything to ensure the victory of their favorite candidates, locally. A few hours before the opening of the ballot, a local candidate was murdered in a violent Western state, adding at least 25 other politicians killed during the election campaign, according to official data.
&nbsp;
In the Mexican state of Puebla, two people died after strangers attacked the polling seats to steal documents, and the votes were suspended in two municipalities of the southern state of Chiapas due to violence. Sheinbaum is committed to carrying out the controversial strategy of the outgoing president "abbraces, not bullets" aimed at facing the crime at the root, while on the contrary his opponent Galvez had promised a harder approach to cartel violence, stating that "the hugs for criminals are over".
<h2> An endless trail of blood
More than 450,000 people have been killed and tens of thousands have disappeared since the government deployed the army to combat drug trafficking in 2006. Among the challenges that the President will face, there are also delicate relations with the neighbouring United States, in particular the controversial issues of cross-border drug trafficking and immigration. Other urgent tasks include the reduction of the poverty rate above 30%> and mitigation of the growing impact of climate change in a country suffering from drought and water shortage.
&nbsp;
On the economic level, Sheinbaum inherits a fiscal deficit of almost 6% of the gross domestic product, despite the austerity promises of Lopez Obrador. In addition, in a country where every day they are killed between 8 and 10 women and sexism is an atavistic problem and rooted, the first female president expects an important action against violence on women. "No one can tell the Mexicans that they are more beautiful if they are quiet," he said during his election campaign.
